This Windham Mt. subdivision, offering 14 prime lots of varying topography and dynamic natural character, overlooks the gently sloping 15.25 acres, facing Windham Mountain. Please note that it is the last great development property, with this type of proximity, adjacent to Windham Mt. The offering took the owner approximately 3.3 years to obtain the proper permitting from various agencies, as Windham lies in the NYC Watershed, and required ample design and planning work by the preeminent engineering firm in the Northern Catskills. There are truly 15 lots, one being made up of a massive pond for the next owner(s) to fish, boat, and enjoy. The owner also completed a high quality road design that wraps around the inner circumference of the 14 lots with excellent grading and run-off, where each driveway would commence. The road, engineering, permitting, grading, and other related costs were nearly $750,000. The owner will, at his expense, move his current luxury home, to one directly on south street, setting the stage for the next owner to start developing with a blank canvas. Once moved, the luxury home and property on south street could be available for purchase. Other than its proximity to the mountain, price, and dynamic terrain, the development is highly accessible to the sewer district, a MAJOR added value. The sewer allows the next developer multiple options, pending local approval. The opportunity allows the next owner to leave the subdivision as it is now, designed for low density private luxury homes, service a high volume of condos or townhomes, or, a unique one family stunning 15.25 acres family compound. The development has a private road entrance from south street, and an access road coming from the east, allowing a quick walk or drive to the slopes and base lodge. The 15.25 acres is comprised of 60% deciduous trees, meadows and fields, all gently sloping upward. Take in the resorts recreation and entertainment throughout the year--skiing, snowboarding, mountain biking, golfing, and special events, as alpine regions in America have recently been seen as safe-havens, protection, and solid long-term investment opportunities. What is majorly lacking is inventory! Any real estate asset proximate to a popular alpine resort is a solid long-term investment, most of them with their own large scale development plans, according to various nationally recognized real estate analytic firms. They are fascinated by what is now known as "The Great Reshuffling." With new virtual work policies, a spike in short term rentals that experts say does not plan on slowing down any time soon, as well as novel new prop-tech financing business models, this property is truly the last of its kind. Windham is uniquely positioned to be a power player in the alpine real estate and development sector in the coming years and it is just over 2 hours from Manhattan.

53.39 acres located in a fertile valley adjacent to the Taconic Mountains in a hamlet called Boston Corners. 

Geographically the property sits at the literal intersection of three states; New York, Massachusetts, and Connecticut, and three wonderful regions; the Hudson Valley, the Berkshires, and the rolling hills of northeast Connecticut. Historically, the property is located in one of the most interesting parts of New York State, if not the country with roots dating back to the early colonel era.  Agriculturally it has been farmed for hundreds of years and continues to be farmed by local farmers. The topography of the property is flat with deep soil.  Water is plentiful and flows down the Taconic Mountains into nearby streams and lakes. Ecologically the property is diverse with grassland birds and butterflies which frequent its meadows and beavers that manage a waterway that runs through the back. Aesthetically the property is a pastoral paradise; a romanized version of the country made true — framed by mountains and farmland. 

Presently, this property has a driveway and building site approved with septic. It also has acreage in agricultural production, in collaboration with a local farmer, as well as pasture and wilderness. Ultimately this property can be subdivided into as many as 10 lots and or kept as a single parcel for a single residence. It has low taxes and flexible building codes, lots of privacy, and state land across the street, which leads up into the Taconic mountains.  

As an investment, the property is a great deal and is presently being offered for $350,000. That’s $6,555 an acre which is lower than any other property in the area. The land is located in an incredibly desirable area with real estate prices on a steady rise and quality land becoming increasingly scarce.

Located in the Leather-stocking Region and a short drive from Cooperstown, this property offers so many opportunities for the new owner: camp or home building sites, agricultural fields, pasture, stream/wetland areas with potential for ponds, and a location near two pristine lakes in an area steeped in beauty, history, and folklore. The property is a beautiful location set up off a quiet but paved, year-round maintained road with flat to gently sloping terrain and another gravel town road with approx. 4054' of road frontage on two sides. There is a farm driveway already into the property. There are several options for building a home or campsites or creating a small farm from the approx. 26 acres of tillable agricultural fields. There are additionally about 30 acres of pasture (some fenced) with creek/wetland. There are a couple of potential options for pond sites and also a small woodlot of approx. 3.5 acres along with tree hedgerows around the property offering cover for wildlife and potential strategic locations for tree stand or ground blinds. Between the ag fields, neighboring woodlands, and brushy undergrowth, this is an excellent habitat for attracting whitetail, wild turkey, grouse, and other area wildlife for cover, bedding, food, and water. In addition to a home or campsite, this property could be a small farm or a great place to provide pasture and turnout for horses or other livestock. Plenty of room to build your perfect getaway camp, cabin, or new home site from the numerous places for potential locations. Additional hunting, camping, hiking, and snowmobiling is available at Exeter State Forest (1957 acres) is approx. 3.2 miles, and Plainfield State Forest (1403 acres) is approx. 7.1 miles away, where the local snowmobile trails are maintained by the Exeter Trail Blazers - offering year-round outdoor activities. New owners also have their choice of outstanding fishing nearby on either Otsego Lake, approx. 4046 acres of pristine water, or Canadarago Lake, a approx. 2000 acre lake and the headwaters of the Susquehanna River, featuring many freshwater fish species, including lake trout, walleye, and perch as the most popular. The Glimmerglass State Park, only approx. 22 miles away, provides approx. 593 acres of natural woodlands, hiking, camping, and a beautiful public beach with picnic grounds. While this property is in a beautiful country setting, amenities, shopping, restaurants, and entertainment are available within a short drive. The town of West Winfield is approx. 8 miles, Richfield Springs is approx. 10 miles away, and Cooperstown is only approx. 17 miles away to the southeast. Cooperstown is world-renowned for its cultural and recreational attractions, including the National Baseball Hall of Fame, Fenimore Art Museum, Farmers Museum, Brewery Ommegang, and Glimmerglass Theatre. Oneonta is approx. 34 miles, Utica is approx. 26 miles, and Albany is approx. 1 hour and 36 minutes away. NYC/George Washington Bridge is just under four hours from this property. The property is being offered as part of a larger parcel, and a new survey has been completed/available.

Whitetail Properties is pleased to present an amazing opportunity to own a piece of American civil war history. Bordering the "Grand Canyon of the East" - Letchworth state park, this property was once the site of the famous Cascade hotel and the original east entrance to the Portage bridge that spanned the Genesee river that majestically roars through the award-winning park. Letchworth State Park was voted the #1 state park in 2015 of over 6000 parks across the country. Further was also voted best attraction in New York state in 2017. The bridge originally required over 300 acres of timber to construct. At the time, it was the longest and tallest wooden bridge in the world, but today has been replaced with a modern steel bridge to connect the east and west sides over the upper falls. This property was the landing site for material for the new bridge, and today has views of the bridge and a look over the upper waterfalls where mist rises in the fall color. The property is wrapped by over 70% borderland with Letchworth State Park for a distance of 8/10'ths of a mile as neighboring property. Inside the park, frequenting visitors would recognize the War memorial that celebrates the First New York Dragoons that trained in Portageville on the parade grounds and shipped off to war to famous battles from the train depot next to the Cascade hotel. They mustered out June 30th, 1865, from here. Most interesting is the original foundation stone for the memorial are on the property to visit. The memorial once called this property its home until it was moved into the park in 1917. Over the years, the owners have found civil war-era artifacts of whisky bottles, lockets, arrows heads, Indian jewelry, etc. They are physical mementos and connections to the past days of a special time in history. The Parade grounds where the troops had trained and staged is at the bottom of the hill, only a mere 1.2 miles away. The Portageville Park Entrance is only 1 mile from the property and is the southwest entrance to the park. The property also is the highest ground on the southeast corner of the park area at 1320 feet, where local balloon rides float by overhead as they tour the falls and park features from above. In more modern times, the popular Finger Lakes trail was established and also wraps the property for those of the hiking spirit. All creatures great and small call this property home. Deer, Turkey, Bear, and even a nesting pair of Bald Eagles are frequently observed on the property. A 2200 sqft home sits on the property that is 75% completed and is located on the bluff edge on the southern border. This could be completed with little work and time or converted into a welcome center for a commercial opportunity. With The way the property is oriented, there is an opportunity to commercially enhance the upper pasture into a campground, RV park, a housing development, or retirement village with premium lots overlooking the southeast bluffs and northwest park border. Trails are established through the woods for access to all corners of the property, and further commercial opportunities present themself for lower development at the base of the bluff. Perhaps you are a history or natural person and would like to keep it well preserved as William Pryor Letchworth did and appropriately keep it natural. His dedication reads, "God wrought for us this scene beyond compare, But one man's loving hand protected it, And gave to his fellow man to share." Check this one out and call for a private tour. Photo Credits: Tom Cook, Tom Breslin, Wikipedia

Well-maintained, freshly painted, move-in ready ranch in a quiet, friendly neighborhood 5 minutes from SUNY New Paltz, downtown New Paltz restaurants and shops, and some of the best hiking trails and scenic views in the Hudson Valley. Easy access to New York City, by bus, train, or car (a 90-minute drive to Manhattan during non-peak hours). This three-bedroom house features a large kitchen, a stunning backyard bordered by mature plantings and trees, a light-filled sun room with a vaulted ceiling, and a two-car garage. A brand new roof was installed last spring (May 2021) by Klaus Larsen, which has an impressive 50-year warranty, and ventilation expanded in the attic to moderate temperature and humidity.

Brand new skylights have been added in the breathtaking floor-to-ceiling windowed sun room, with a vaulted ceiling and views of nature in three directions. (Four if you include the skylights!) Equipped with cordless bamboo shades and custom matching skylight shades on every window to keep light in or heat out, the sun room features a sliding door which opens onto an original blue stone patio. Both patio and sun room face the enormous backyard, bordered in the back by tall trees so that the property feels both spacious and secluded. The half-acre property includes two raised gardening beds, a fire pit, and a post perfectly situated for hanging a hammock. Botanical features include lilac bushes, a Japanese maple tree, a magnolia tree, and an array of other perennial trees and wildflowers.

The primary bedroom of the house fits a king-size bed with room to spare. The original hardwood floors go throughout the main house and are freshly finished. The kitchen—well-equipped for the serious cook—is outfitted with stainless steel appliances: a new Samsung induction range, a professional quality Hauslane vented range hood, and a Bosch dishwasher. Also updated: the furnace-integrated water heater and water piping throughout the house.

A dedicated laundry room includes a utility sink and basement-level drain pump. The basement also features a well-maintained well water purification system, oil heating system, and an early 1900s woodworking bench. The two-car garage has access to the stunning backyard.

"The Anchorage "
A rare opportunity to own one of the largest waterfront properties in Rye. 5.9  pastoral acres and 4.4 underwater acres totaling 10.3 acres. A premier coastal estate with an historic home sited upon high elevation with endless views of the Long Island Sound. Formerly owned by the President of Paramount Pictures, the Anchorage was used as the secret filming location for "Sabrina" with Audrey Hepburn and Humphrey Bogart. Its secluded waterfront is featured in the opening and sailing scenes.

A magnificent brick Georgian Colonial designed by the distinguished architect Mott B.Schmidt,  Multileveled brick terraces were designed by renowned landscape architect Ellen Biddle Shipman. A broad rolling lawn, framed by mature tulip and beech trees, slopes down to a semicircular sea wall enveloping a private sandy beach. The view is sublime throughout every season. 
   An architectural masterpiece with eight fireplaces, six bedrooms, three maid's rooms, a third-floor bedroom/ exercise room, mother-in-law’s suite, and beautiful views from every window. The building’s construction is of the highest quality, with red brick and white trim and thick interior plaster walls.
The Anchorage was the paradigm for Mott Schmidt’s long and distinguished career. “ Mott Schmidt created many sumptuous residences in his trademark American Georgian style for the city’s society and business elite,” stated architect Robert A. M. Stern.” As the master of proportion, Schmidt’s brilliance is seen in the graceful, restrained restatement of the American Georgian vocabulary.
   Classical simplicity is achieved in the formal entry hall with classical architectural details accented by Schmidt’s signature elegant curving staircase.  The living and dining room have oak parquet floors and a wall of French doors opening out towards the Sound. 
   A European-imported paneled library with magnificent wood carving.  A breakfast room overlooks an in-ground pool and garden terrace. The garden room overlooks the West lawn and  Van Amringe Pond.  You will never want to leave this tranquil oasis.

The historic estate includes an 1850 ‘s carriage house/barn, cottage, and 750 sq ft boathouse/artist studio. (Selling as is). 
A 40-minute commute to Grand Central and a 1/2 hour drive to Manhattan. Close to public and private schools. Numerous golf and yacht clubs are nearby.
